## Understanding the CSS `:not()` Pseudo-class

According to [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Reference/Selectors/:not):

> The **`:not()`** CSS pseudo-class represents elements that do not match a list of selectors. Since it prevents specific items from being selected, it is known as the *negation pseudo-class*.

In simple terms, **`:not()` means ‚Äúselect everything except this.‚Äù**

### Basic example

```css
/* 
  Select all button elements except those with the class .primary
*/
button:not(.primary) {
  opacity: 0.6;
}
```

This selector targets every `button` that does *not* have the `.primary` class.

---

## Using `:not()` for a Hover Effect

The powerful thing about **`:not()`** is that it can exclude not only classes, but also other pseudo-classes such as **`:hover`**, **`:active`**, and **`:focus`**.

Let‚Äôs try applying it to our list items:

```css
.item-link:not(:hover) {
  opacity: 0.2;
  transition: 0.3s ease;
}

```

### Why this isn‚Äôt enough

If you try this, all list items will be dimmed **unless they are hovered**.\
This effect works, but it‚Äôs not what we want ‚Äî it could be achieved with a simple `:hover` rule.

Our goal is different:

- Items should dim **only when one of them is hovered**
- When nothing is hovered, everything should stay visible

---

## Fixing the Hover Behavior

To fix this, we need to make the effect conditional on the **parent container being hovered**.

```css
.container:hover .item-link:not(:hover) {
  opacity: 0.2;
  transition: 0.3s ease;
}

```

Now the logic becomes:

- When the container is hovered
- Dim all items **except** the one currently hovered

This gets us very close to the desired result.

---

## Preventing the Container Hover Issue

There‚Äôs one remaining problem.

When the cursor enters the **`.container`** but is not hovering a specific item, all items still become dimmed. This happens because the container itself is hovered.

To fix this, we can make the container ignore pointer events:

```css
.container {
  pointer-events: none;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  height: 100vh;
}

```

Each `.item-link` still receives hover events, but the container itself no longer does ‚Äî exactly what we need.

---

## When Should You Use This Technique?

This CSS hover pattern works especially well for:

- Navigation menus
- Feature lists
- Card-based layouts
- Image or content galleries

It‚Äôs ideal when you want to **guide user attention** without adding JavaScript or complex logic.
